    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Stability Testing and Design of Multidimensional Recursive Digital Filters</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Rathinam.A</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Stability Testing<br />Multidimensional Recursive Digital</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Jan-2014 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0135</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">In multidimensional digital signal processing, filters are more concerned
with the processing of signals available in the form of sampled images or sampled
time waveforms. These signals which are represented as multidimensional arrays are
received or collected simultaneously from several input sensors. Multidimensional
digital signal processing is quite different from one dimensional digital signal
processing due to the following three factors:
1. Two-dimensional problems generally involve considerably more data than
one dimensional ones.
2. The mathematics for handling multidimensional systems is less complete
than the mathematics for handling one dimensional system.
3. Multidimensional systems have many more degrees of freedom, which gives
a system designer the flexibility that is not encountered in the one
dimensional case.
Numerous methods for the design, stability testing and real time
implementation of 2-D &amp; multi-dimensional recursive filters have been developed
by researchers in the last three decades. Due to the increased complexity of
calculations in multi-dimensions, the stability testing of multi-dimensional filters is
an intricate one.
Stability testing of 2-D and multidimensional filters is carried out either
by algebraic or mapping methods. In algebraic methods, stability can be determined
in a finite number of steps. The accuracy of the algebraic methods is affected by the
finite word length effects of the computer. Even for a low order filter, algebraic
methods require large number of calculations. So this method consumes relatively
larger time to find the exact stability. Even though the algebraic methods have few
such practical limitations in the implementation, the steps involved are finite in
nature.
Unlike algebraic methods, mapping methods cannot guarantee the
stability of the given recursive digital filter in a finite number of steps. The mapping
methods can determine the stability, in an infinite number of steps. Irrespective of
the filters’ order, either high or low, the calculations do not increase enormously and
the exactness of the decision on the stable or unstable nature of the filters is highly
reliable.
The advantages of algebraic and mapping methods, namely stability
determination in finite number of steps and guaranteed stability results respectively,
have been focused on in this work.
Two simplified procedures for the stability testing of multidimensional
filters (m-D) based on an algebraic method which uses evaluation of complex
integrals and a mapping method which uses simplified row and column
concatenation method are presented.
For converting the multi-dimensional filters into low order 1-D, 2-D, etc,
Decarlo-Strintzis theorem on multidimensional filters is adopted. A simple two step
algebraic procedure adopted for 2-D Quarter Plane filters is extended to
multidimensional filters. The simplified row and column concatenation method uses
a unique value of L to indicate the unstable nature of the filter although the
instability may be indicated by other L values.

The proposed methods are applied to barely stable or unstable filter
literature examples which are devoid of non-essential singularities of the second
kind. It is observed that both the procedures simplified the calculations and are
correct in terms of the available literature results. The simplified procedure using
mapping method is found to be conceptually straightforward, easy, accurate and fast
for identifying the unstable nature of the filters.
In order to overcome the limitations of the conventional testing
procedures such as larger number of calculations, longer processing time etc,
artificial neural networks based stability testing procedure is considered. The various
types of neural networks considered are Feed-forward architecture with error backpropagation
algorithm, resilient back-propagation algorithm, Radial basis function
networks, Extreme learning machines (ELM), Radial Basis function–extreme
learning machine networks (RBF-ELM) and Probabilistic neural networks (PNN).
The performance of the networks are measured and monitored in training &amp; testing
process with the aim of ascertaining the suitability of ANN technique towards the
stability testing procedure.
In literature, Design procedure for the two dimensional filters has been
addressed either by an appropriate transformation to one dimensional filters or by an
optimisation technique. In this work, the design task is formulated as a constrained
minimisation problem. An attempt is made to include the stability criteria in the
design process in terms of the constraints. A new intelligent optimisation algorithm,
namely Firefly algorithm, is utilised to solve the minimisation design problem of the
2-D IIR filters. Test results of the new algorithm provide a better design in
considerably lesser time.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13841">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13841</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
